"(1) (i) The air bit with the sharp promise of winter as stepped onto the cracked, sun-blasted plaza of . Around him, sculptures shimmered in the pale morning light—tall, spindly figures of animals frozen mid-stride, their glass and crystal skin glinting like fractured moonlight. Laughter and the faint hiss of melting icicles drifted from the crowd, mingling with the scent of cold stone and distant coffee. Conducted ice preservation talks.\n(2) He moved through the throng, clipboard tucked under his arm, acutely aware that his own words would echo far beyond these walls, even as they dissolved into the air. (ii) He paused before a sprawling, jagged phoenix, its wings frozen in a storm of blue and violet shards. Children pressed close, breath fogging in the chill, pointing at the impossible feathers.\n(3) Benjamin’s throat tightened; he remembered the last time he’d spoken before such an audience, the nervous flutter in his chest, the way his voice had wavered. The crowd’s attention was a fragile thing, easily scattered by the wind or a sudden gust. He took a steadying breath, the familiar weight of responsibility settling over him like a shawl.\n(4) (iii) A woman in a navy coat approached, her eyes drawn to a delicate swan mid-flight. “How do you keep the sculptures from melting?” she asked, voice tentative, as if afraid of the answer. Benjamin smiled, but it felt brittle.\n(5) He began to explain the science of ice crystals, the importance of controlled temperature and vapor barriers, his explanations careful and precise. Yet, behind the lecture, he felt the sting of old failures—talks that ended in silence, questions he couldn’t answer, the cold that never quite left. (iv) The crowd ebbed and flowed like tides, shifting around him as artists arrived with new pieces. Benjamin Green.\n(6) One sculptor, young and intense, handed him a chisel still warm from the studio. “Help me fix this crack,” he said, desperation in his eyes. Benjamin’s hands shook as he reached for the tool.\n(7) The ice was so fragile, so easily broken, and yet here was a man risking his reputation on a single flaw. The tragedy of it all pressed in on. Washington Square Park. February 27, 2026."